{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_crane_ver01/data/sn85053157/0029586087A/1907102301/0363.xml":{"full_text":"O\nThere Is 17o Financial\nPanic in Sight.\nP.y LESLIE M. SHAW, Former Secretary of the Treasury.\nUK farms produce mure than $0,500,000,000 per an\nnum, ami TILE PROSPECT IS GOOD for an av\nerage crop. Our mines yield more than $1,500,000,\n000 and our forests more than $1,000,000,000. And\nneither of these sources of wealth has been exhausted.\nThe output of our factories in other than food prod\nucts is approximately $12,000,000,000, and no fires have been extin\nguished.\nThe railways earn more than $2,000,000,000, and THEY ABE\nALL IN SUCCESSFUL OPERATION. The payrolls of our facto\nries and railways aggregate approximately $3,500,000,000, and the\nscale of wages has not been reduced.\nIN OTHER WORD8, THE REAL 80URCES OF THE PEOPLE'8\nWEALTH HAVE NOT YET BEEN AFFECTED, AND THE ABILITY OF\nINDUSTRIAL CONCERN8 TO PAY DIVIDENDS 18 NOT MEA8URED\nBY THE MARKET PRICE OF THEIR STOCKS.\n\u00abI n\nBy HENRY C. FRICK of the United States Steel Corporation.\nI FIND NOTHING IN UNDERLYING CONDITIONS TO WARRANT\nTHE APPARENT GREAT LACK OF CONFIDENCE IN BUSINESS GEN\nERALLY WHICH NOW 8EEM8 PREVALENT. IF THERE 18 ANY\nTHING TO JUSTIFY THAT FEELING IN TRADE CONDITIONS, I\nDO NOT SEE IT.\nI can understand the VAGUE, BUT REAL UNSETTLEMENT\nOF SENTIMENT created by current agitation against corporations,\nbut this is in a measure apart from real conditions and is capable of\ncorrection. I believe myself, and always have, in the correction of\nABUSES, WHETHER CORPORATE OR INDIVIDUAL, but I\nfeel that such care should be exercised in doing this that only the\nwrongdoer should suffer.\nOf course where corporations are still acting outside of the law\nUNKNOWINGLY it is to bo expected that they should bo set right,\nbut I am sure they can be accomplished without harm to any one and\nwithout the least injury to credit, if the situation is PROPERLY\nAND INTELLIGENTLY HANDLED by the administration.\nn n n\nBy JOSEPH C. CANNON, Speaker of the National House of Representatives.\nBOSH, ALL BOSH! THAT'S WHAT IT IS, THIS TALK OF\nFINANCIAL RUIN. THE COUNTRY NEVER WAS BETTER, AND I\nGUESS THESE WALL STREET FELLOWS ARE SQUEALING BE\nCAUSE THEY'VE BEEN STUNG.\nWith me it's simply a question of whether the bulls oat the bears\nor the bears cat the bulls. There happens to be A FEW MILLION\nFARMERS in this country of ours, and they are not bothering about\nthis cry of financial panic. They're busy harvesting their crops.\nNO FEAR, THE FARMERS WILL BE BUYING MORE AUTOMO\nBILES THIS FALL, AND INSTEAD OF DISASTER THERE WILL BE\nMORE REAL PROSPERITY THAN EVER BEFORE. REAL PROS\nPERITY, I SAID, NOT THE WALL STREET KIND.\nm r\nBy WILLIAM B. RIDGELY, Comptroller of the Currency.\nThe announcement made by Secretary Cortelyou of his plan for\nrelieving the strain on the money market by the deposit of govern\nment funds is E Il WISE AND TIMELY and should go verv\nfar toward allaying apprehension and restoring business to its normal\ncondition.\nWHILE THE PRESENT SITUATION IS ONE REQUIRING CARE\nAND COOL HEADED, DELIBERATE ACTION, ESPECIALLY ON THE\nPART OF THE BANKS, THERE IS NO REASON AT ALL WHY THE\nDEMAND FOR LIQUIDATION SHOULD SO SPREAD AS TO PRODUCE\nANYTHING LIKE A PANIC OR COMMERCIAL CRISIS.\nThe banking condition is UNUSUALLY SOUND, more so on\naccount of the readjustment of stock market values.\nNational Control of\nIndustry Is Inevitable.\nBy Dr. CHARLES J. BUSMNl l l, Sociologist, of Washington.\nCUE modern trust is the response under individualistic condi\ntions to the inevitable demand for a MORE UNIFIED\nAND ECONOMICAL business organization. And Social\nism itself, with all its past faults and failures, is but the\nIl R I II KK EFFORT to carry the will of the people effectively into\nour industrial as well as our political life.\nBY ITS DEMAND THAT WE SHOULD OWN AND CONTROL\nCOLLECTIVELY WHAT WE NEED TO USE COLLECTIVELY, SOCIAL\nISM IS A PROTEST AGAINST THE THEORY THAT ALL A WORK\nINGMAN NEEDS AND WANTS IS A ROOF, A FAMILY AND A FULL\nDINNER PAIL. IT IS AN ASPIRATION FOR A FULLER AND\nNOBLER SOCIAL LIFE.\nFor one I believe that the present UNDENIABLE DECAY OF\nDEMOCRATIC INSTITUTIONS, of government of, for and by\nthe people, is temporary and is slowly arousing a reaction which is\nbound to lead us into a finer and a broader national life, with adequate\nNATIONAL CONTROL of our irreat industries.\nAmerica Not the\nLand of the Free.\nBy Sir CASPAR PURDON CLARKE. Director of the Metropolitan Museum\nof Art. New York.\nHMERICA is not the land of liberty. Your blue ribbon laws\nthat make the temperate suffer for the intemperate aiv most\nTYRANNICAL. In England at least we have no laws in\nterfering with personal rights.\nTALK ABOUT OPPRESSION IN RUSSIA! WHERE WILL YOU\nFIND ANY GREATER OPPRESSION THAN IN THE STATE OF\nMAINE, WITH ITS UNJUST BLUE LAWS? FREEDOM! AMERICA\nCANNOT BOAST OF THAT.\nIt is WOMEN WHO ARE REALLY AT THE BOTTOM\nOF TUESi'. BLUE RIBBON LAWS, these t\\mimical restriction's\nof personal liberty. Whenever a woman permits her emotions to run\naway with her judgment she is almost sure t>> rush into something of\nthis kind. Women are all riuht until tliev become FADDISTS.\nMONTANA BRIEFLETS.\nSHORT ITEMS OF NEWS FROM\nALL OVER THE STATE.\nWhat Has Happened in Montana Dur\ning the Past Few Days.\ni\nButte Oct. 17.\u2014The estimated pro\nduction of the Butte mines in Septem\nber was 11,329,800 pounds of copper.\nThis compares with an estimated pro\nduction of 23,227,240 pounds in Au\ngust and 27,157,395 pounds in July.\nThe decrease from the August produc\ntion is 11,799,440 pounds, or 51 per\ncent.\nHelena Oct. 17 \u2014A ten thousand\ndollar potato crop from a compara\ntively small ranch is what was raised\nthis year by Rogan Brother's, who live\ndown in the valley a short distance.\nRogans raised 10,000 sacks o! potatoes\nand are receiving a dollar per sack.\nMaurice Weiss has purchased 75,000\npounds which are now being delivered.\nButte Oct. 17.\u2014J. B. Sullivan and\nPat Kelleher, two Butte miners, while\nexploring the old workings of the old\nMoulton mine north of Walkerville\nyesterday were astounded to discover\na store of 78 old Springfield rifles,\nhidden away behind an old bulkhead.\nThe rifles are of the pattern used by\nthe army years ago and were stacked\nin an old stope, which bad been sealed\nup by the bulkhead.\nL ewistown Oct. 17.\u2014 The bequest\nof $2,000 made to the public library\nby the late Oscar Stephens has just\nbeen paid into the city treasury by\nFrank Stephens,the administrator, and\nthis led to the passage of an ordinance\nby which the policy of the city with\nregard to such bequests is fixed. Only\nthe interest of the Stephens' gift is to be\nused, and it is to be applied exclusive\nly to the purchase of books, to be\nknown as the Stephens collection.\nLewistown Oct. 18.\u2014William\nBeacon, known in many parts of\nMontana as \"Sure Shot Bill,\" and\nfor years one of the most noted sport\ning men on the coast, was found dead\nin the cabin on his ranch near Gilt\nEdge. Beason made and lost for\ntunes at the gambling table, but gave\nnp that life a few years ago.\nCheat Falls Oct. 18.\u2014 The direc\ntors of the Northern Montana Fair\nassociation today announced that the\nassociation lost $852.57 on the recent\nfair held in this city, the deficit being\ndue to bad weather the last two days,\nwhereby the attendance on each day\nwas considerably curtailed. The loss\nwill be made up by the sale of stock\nof the association.\nHelena Oct. 18.\u2014a tlag staff fifty\nfeet in height is being erected on the\ncapitol grounds in accordance with\nthe bill passed by the last legislature,\nwhich provided funds for the placing\nof the 11 ag pole on the grounds and\nalso for the purchase of a silk llag\nwhich will fly from the pole. Men are\nat work digging holes for the pole and\nfor the supports to which guy wires\nwill be attached. The staff will be in\nplace and ready for the stars and\nstripes within a week, and when the\ntlag is raised it will be visible from\nall parts of the city.\nDeer Loix;k Oct. 18.\u2014j. l. Ivel ley,\nwho was sent to the penitentiary from\nMissoula, made a most sensational\nescape last night, from a train, while\niu charge of an officer, and to the\npresent he has not been apprehended.\nHe was handcuffed and after the train\npassed Garrison he opened a window\nand jumped out while the train was\nmaking 35 miles an hour. The train\nstopped, but no trace of Kelley could\nbe found. Bloodhound\u00bb from the\npenitentiary are to be put on his trail.\nL ewistown Oct. 19.\u2014P. O.Oram, a\nlaborer on the Billings Northern\nrailway construction near Stanford,\nwas fouud murdered near that place\nearly this morning, he haviug been\nlain in a most cold-blooded manner\nby two men, whose motive for the\nrime was the desire to secure a little\nmoney in the victim's possession.\nThe murdedrers have not been appre\nhended.\nButte Oct. 19.\u2014Charles O' tiara,\nconvicted of manslaughter for shoot\ning and itilliny James Noon an iu this\ncity a year ago was sentenced to nine\nyears in the penitentiary this morning\nin the criminal department of district\ncourt. The court told him that the\nkilling of Noonan was a \"cowardly\nmurder,\" that he \"shot Noonan from\nbehind like an Indian,\" and that the\ncourt would give him \"credit\" for the\nyear he has served in the county jail\nHelena Oct. 19.\u2014 Governor S. T\nIlauser, who has just returned from\nthe east, aunouuees that the project to\nbuild a third dam on the Missouri\nriver for the reclamation of land in\nthe Prickly Fear valley will be carried\nout, and that the necessary money for\nthe work has been secured. The first\narea of land to be reclaimed will be\n30,000 acres. The final area will be\nfrom l '0,000 to 120,000 acres.\nHelena Oct. 19.\u2014By the ups ttiug\nof a boat ou Lake llauser some time\nbetween Friday and early yesterday\nmoruiug, three negroes, it is believed,\nwere drowned. The three men had\ngone out ou a duck hunt and left a\nhorse and buggy in a shed near the\nlake. The boat in which they set out\nfloated ashore duri\u00fcg the morning and\nup to an early hour this morning a\nrescue party had been unable to locate j\nthe men or to recover their bodies.\nLittle doubt is entertained that all 1\nthree of the men perished in the lake.\nVALUE OF A WH00PER.\nIndian Territory Hunters Introduced\nto a New Character.\nA Muskogee (I. T.) hunting party on\nthe brakes of the Illinois river had\npitched its tents for the night; the hunt\ners had eaten supper and were smok\ning a pipeful of \"home grown\" before\nturning in. They intended to get a\ngood rest and begin their hunt the next\nmorning. While they were spinning\nyarns a barefooted country boy bash\nfully sauntered up to the campfire and\nInquired whether or not they wanted\nto hire a \"whooper,\" writes a Musko\ngee correspondent of the Kansas City\nStar.\n\"What Is a whooper?\" asked one of\nthe hunters.\n\"A whooper's a whooper,\" said the\nboy in surprise. 'Pears to me you all\nain't much hunters If you don't know\nwhat a whooper Is.\"\nMore to have sport with the boy\nthan anything else the lad was hired.\nWhen the hunting party started into\nthe canebrake the next morning the\nboy said:\n\"Now, when you all is lost just\nwhoop 'er up, and I'll whoop back, and\nyou all come to my whoop.\"\nIn the afternoon one of the hunters\ntried to go back to camp, but lost his\nway. About the time he thought he\nwould strike a clearing he would find\nthe canebrake growing thicker. He\nhad almost given up iu despair when\nhe thought of the whooper. He let\nout a yell and listened.\n\"Whoopee!\" came the sound from\nthe distance. He knew the whooper\nhad lived up to his contract. By fol\nlowing the souud made by the boy the\nhunter struck the clearing and got\nback to camp iu safety.\n\"It's a cinch If a man goes hunting\non the Illinois,\" said this hunter, \"he'd\nbetter employ a whooper.\"\nA Rhyming Will.\nPerhaps the most peculiar will ever\nwritten was probated lu England at\ndoctors' commons, July 17, 1789. It\nran as follows:\nI ftivo and bequeath,\nWhen I am laid underneath.\nTo my two loving sisters, most dear,\nThe whole of my store,\nWere it twice as much more,\nWhich God's goodness has granted me\nhere.\nAnd that none may prevent\nThis my wilt and intent,\nOr occasion the least of law racket,\nWith a solemn appeal\nI confirm, sign and seal\nThis the true act and deed of Will Jacket.\n\u2014Chicago Record-Herald.\nA Wonderful Creature.\nHie polyp Is the most remarkable\ncreature ou earth. If cut transversely\nor longitudinally iuto several parts,\neach will become a perfect animal.\nTrembly turned them inside out and\nthey ate and enjoyed themselves as\nmuch as ever. He slit two longltudl\nnaliy, placed the halves together and\nunited them into two animals. He\ndivided two transversely and created\none with two heads. He pushed one\ndown the throat of another, a third\ndown the throat of the second, and thus\nformed a creature with three heads.\nSPECIALIST\nPRESCRIBES\nA Famous French Specialist on Dis\neases of the Skin Prescribes Cuti\ncura as the Most Effective Remedy\nKnown to Him, Charging as His\nFee 100 Francs ($20).\nALSO PRESCRIBED IN\nHOSPITAL SAINT LOUIS\nGentlemen You may hp pleased to\nlearn that a patient suffering from an\nirritation of the skin, caused by motor\ning, on consulting a noted physician in\nParis, for which a fee of one hundred\nfrancs (twenty dollars) was charged,\nwas advised to use Cuticura. which ad\nvice, although received with astonish\nment, was fol! -v I und resulted in a\nperfect cure. >s. ned) Lewis Gower,\n1123 Broadway. New York, U. S. A.,\nDecember Hi, i'.Hhi.\"\nFrench physicians, particularly those\nmaking a specialty of the treatment of\nskin diseases, have for many years re\ngarded Cuticura as a specific and have\nprescribed it freely. It enjoys the rare\ndistinction of l>eing prescribed in the\nHospital Saint Louis. Paris, one of the\nlargest and most famous hospitals in\nthe world devoted exclusively to the\ntreatment of diseases of the skiu.\nMother Of Ten\nAlways Kept Cuticura Ready\nfor Children's Skin and\nScalp Troubles.\n\"I wish to add my voice to the praise\nof Cuticura Remedies. 1 am the father\nof ten children, whose mother is dead.\nIn our homes in England and America,\nshe kept in her little medicine chest,\nalways on hand, and often used to use the\nCuticura Remedies, and they brought\nthe best of results in children's skin and\nscalp troubles. These children are all\ngrown and scattered and 1 cannot recall\nany specific cases of eure, but 1 do know\nthat 1 have spent remarkably little in\ndoctors' ftvs. George \\Y. Rugby. X,\nClarkSt., Chicago, 111., Oct. 2\">. l'.Hlti.\"\nComplot\u00ab\"\u00bb External and lntorr.nl Treatment for\nEvery Humor of Infants, Children, and Adults. con\nsists ,<f Cuticura Sou\u00bb t2.V to Cleanse the >kin,\nCuticura Ointment t\u00f4Oo to Heal the skin. :ind Cuti\ncura Resolvent tor in the form \u00ab.f chorolnte\nCoated Pills. 2.V. per vial of t>0> to Purify the Hl<>- d.\nSold throughout the world, Potter l>ru, T Chtra.\nCorn Sole Pr u>s B \u00bbst in. Mas\u00bb.\nULTMailcd Irec. Cuticura Hook 0:1 Skiu Diseases.\n\u00c2NfegetabiePreparationlbrAs\nsUn\u00dcatirig thfFoodandRetf ula\nHrt g rtia StrwawM and R owp L s of\nI m wis il i id it i\nSrainotesTSgksfloivCfaeetl'ul\nOnu\u00e2CMorpbin\u00e9 nor Mineral.\nMot Nahcotic.\nt&OUa&iNCZLVtlVMB\nSmi'\ntion. Sour .Stomach.Diarrhoea\nWonns'\u00a3onvulsions,Feverish\n0 (55 and Loss OF S leep.\nVise Simile Signat ure of\nNEW YOHK.\nexact copy or wrapper.\nCUSTOM\u00bb\nFor Infants and Children.\nThe Kind You Have\nAlways Bought\nBears the\nSignature\nIn\nuSG\nFor Over\nThirty Years\n(ASTORIA\nTNK CENTAUR COMPANY. NEW YORK 6ITV.\nAra Y nu a oser of illuminating oil?\nAIC 1UU If you are,\nDon't Forget\nWe are now